  clusterTitle="Load Calculation"
>

  <!-- ─── Quick Answer ─── -->
  <QuickAnswerBox id="quick-answer">
    <p>
      An average Indian home uses <strong>100–300 units (kWh) of electricity per month</strong>, which works out
      to roughly <strong>3–10 units per day</strong>. The biggest variable is air conditioning — a single 1.5 Ton AC
      running 8 hours a day adds ~13 units daily (about 400 units/month) all by itself. A 1 BHK without AC
      typically uses 80–120 units/month; a 3 BHK with two ACs can easily consume 400–700 units/month.
    </p>
  </QuickAnswerBox>

  <!-- ─── Visual Explanation ─── -->
  <h2 id="visual-explanation">Home Size vs Typical Monthly Electricity Consumption</h2>

  <p>
    One "unit" of electricity is 1 kilowatt-hour (kWh) — the energy consumed when a 1,000-watt appliance
    runs for exactly one hour. Your electricity bill states how many units you've consumed in the billing cycle.
    The table below shows typical monthly consumption ranges for different Indian home configurations.
  </p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Home Type</th>
          <th>Bedrooms</th>
          <th>Monthly Units (kWh)</th>
          <th>Monthly Cost (₹5/unit)</th>
          <th>Annual Cost</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>1 BHK, No AC</td>
          <td>1</td>
          <td>80–120 units</td>
          <td>₹400–600</td>
          <td>₹4,800–7,200</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2 BHK, No AC</td>
          <td>2</td>
          <td>120–200 units</td>
          <td>₹600–1,000</td>
          <td>₹7,200–12,000</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2 BHK, 1 AC (1.5 Ton)</td>
          <td>2</td>
          <td>250–400 units</td>
          <td>₹1,250–2,000</td>
          <td>₹15,000–24,000</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>3 BHK, 2 ACs</td>
          <td>3</td>
          <td>400–700 units</td>
          <td>₹2,000–3,500</td>
          <td>₹24,000–42,000</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>4 BHK, 3+ ACs</td>
          <td>4</td>
          <td>700–1,200 units</td>
          <td>₹3,500–6,000</td>
          <td>₹42,000–72,000</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>Note:</strong> These are estimates based on typical Indian urban usage patterns. Actual consumption
    varies significantly with climate (hotter cities use more AC), appliance efficiency ratings (5-star vs
    1-star), occupancy hours, and individual habits. Slab tariffs also mean per-unit cost rises as you
    consume more.
  </p>

  <p>
    The AC is the single biggest lever in your electricity bill. In most Indian climates, switching from
    a 1-star to a 5-star rated 1.5 Ton AC saves approximately 600–800 units per year — worth ₹3,000–4,000
    annually at average tariff rates.
  </p>

  <!-- ─── Step-by-Step ─── -->
  <h2 id="step-by-step">Step-by-Step: How to Calculate Your Monthly Consumption</h2>

  <p>
    You don't need to wait for your electricity bill to understand your consumption. Here's how to estimate
    your monthly kWh (units) for any appliance or your entire home using a simple formula:
  </p>

  <p style="text-align:center;font-family:var(--font-mono);background:var(--bg-card);border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:0.75rem;padding:1rem;margin:1.5rem 0;">
    <strong>Monthly Units = (Watts × Hours per Day × 30) ÷ 1,000</strong>
  </p>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong>List every appliance and its wattage</strong>
      <p>
        Find the wattage rating on the product label or user manual. For ACs, a 1 Ton AC uses ~1,100W,
        a 1.5 Ton uses ~1,600W, and a 2 Ton uses ~2,000W. Refrigerators use about 150–250W on average
        (they cycle on and off, so "average" watts matter more than peak watts).
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Estimate daily usage hours for each appliance</strong>
      <p>
        Be realistic. A ceiling fan might run 10–12 hours. An AC might run 6–10 hours in summer and
        0–2 hours in winter. Your refrigerator runs 24 hours but only actively cools for about 8–10 hours
        (compressor on-time). A TV might run 4–6 hours. A geyser typically runs 30–60 minutes per day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Calculate daily kWh for each appliance</strong>
      <p>
        Daily kWh = Watts × Hours ÷ 1,000. Example: 1.5 Ton AC (1,600W) running 8 hours =
        1,600 × 8 ÷ 1,000 = <strong>12.8 kWh per day</strong>. A ceiling fan (75W, 10 hours) =
        75 × 10 ÷ 1,000 = <strong>0.75 kWh per day</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Multiply by 30 for monthly units</strong>
      <p>
        Monthly kWh = Daily kWh × 30. The AC from the example: 12.8 × 30 = <strong>384 units/month</strong>.
        The ceiling fan: 0.75 × 30 = <strong>22.5 units/month</strong>. Add up all appliances for your
        total monthly consumption estimate.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">5</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Add standby / phantom loads (5–10% extra)</strong>
      <p>
        Every device with a standby mode (TV with remote, set-top box, phone chargers, WiFi router,
        microwave with clock display) consumes 1–5W continuously. For a typical home, these "vampire
        loads" add up to 50–100W running 24/7 — that's 36–72 kWh per month. Add 5–10% to your
        calculated total to account for this.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="step-number">6</div>
    <div>
      <strong>Use our free calculator to verify</strong>
      <p>
        Our <a href="/" data-astro-prefetch="hover">Electricity Load Calculator</a> lets you add every
        appliance with quantity and usage hours, and instantly shows your total connected load in kW,
        daily kWh, and monthly units — no spreadsheet needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Real Example ─── -->
  <h2 id="real-example">Real Example: A 2BHK Home Calculation</h2>

  <div class="example-box">
    <p class="example-label">2 BHK Home — Monthly Electricity Breakdown</p>
    <p>
      Let's walk through a typical 2BHK home in a tier-1 Indian city with a family of 4,
      with 1 × 1.5 Ton AC in the bedroom (used 8 hours/day during summer, say 5 months/year),
      and standard appliances running year-round.
    </p>

    <p><strong>Year-round appliances (monthly consumption):</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>4 × Ceiling Fan (75W, 10 hr/day): 4 × 75 × 10 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>90 units</strong></li>
      <li>8 × LED Bulb (10W, 6 hr/day): 8 × 10 × 6 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>14.4 units</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Refrigerator (200W avg, 24 hr/day): 200 × 24 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>144 units</strong></li>
      <li>1 × TV 40" (90W, 5 hr/day): 90 × 5 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>13.5 units</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Washing Machine (500W, 1 hr/day): 500 × 1 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>15 units</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Laptop (60W, 6 hr/day): 60 × 6 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>10.8 units</strong></li>
      <li>Standby loads (~80W, 24 hr/day): 80 × 24 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>57.6 units</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Year-round subtotal: ~345 units/month</strong></p>

    <p><strong>Summer months only (May–Sep, ~5 months):</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>1 × 1.5 Ton AC (1,600W, 8 hr/day): 1600 × 8 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>384 units</strong></li>
      <li>1 × Geyser (2,000W, 0.5 hr/day in winter) → Negligible in summer</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Summer months total: ~729 units/month</strong></p>

    <p><strong>Winter months only (Nov–Feb, ~4 months):</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>1 × Geyser (2,000W, 0.5 hr/day): 2000 × 0.5 × 30 ÷ 1000 = <strong>30 units</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Winter months total: ~375 units/month</strong></p>

    <p>
      <strong>Annual consumption:</strong> (345 × 12) + (384 × 5) + (30 × 4) = 4,140 + 1,920 + 120 = <strong>~6,180 units/year</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Average monthly: ~515 units</strong> — consistent with the 2 BHK + 1 AC range of 250–700 units/month.
      At ₹6/unit average (after slab tariff), that's approximately <strong>₹3,100/month</strong>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ─── Reference Table ─── -->
  <h2 id="reference-table">Appliance Consumption Reference Table</h2>

  <p>
    Use this table to quickly look up how many units your individual appliances consume per day and per month.
