  <!-- ─── Common Mistakes ─── -->
  <h2 id="common-mistakes">Common Mistakes When Estimating Electricity Usage</h2>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Not accounting for AC usage variation by season</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        An AC running 8 hours/day in May adds ~384 units/month. The same AC in December might add
        only 20–30 units. If you calculate an annual average without considering seasonal variation,
        your summer bills will be a shock. Always model your consumption season by season, especially
        for cities like Delhi, Chennai, or Hyderabad with extreme summer temperatures.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Forgetting standby and phantom loads</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Devices left on standby — set-top box, smart TV, phone chargers left plugged in, WiFi router,
        microwave with a clock display — can collectively consume 100–200W continuously. Over 30 days,
        that's 72–144 kWh you're paying for without getting much benefit. Use smart power strips or
        turn off devices at the switch when not in use.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Using peak watts instead of average watts for cycling appliances</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        A refrigerator's compressor might peak at 350W but averages only 150–200W because it cycles
        on and off. Similarly, an inverter AC's variable compressor means actual power draw fluctuates
        constantly. Using peak power for 24-hour appliances wildly overestimates consumption. Check
        the appliance's energy label for Annual Energy Consumption (kWh/year) — this is the most
        accurate number.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Ignoring star rating differences between appliances</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        A 5-star rated 1.5 Ton inverter AC (ISEER 5+) uses roughly 40% less electricity than a
        1-star non-inverter model for the same cooling output. Over 5 years of use, the 5-star model
        saves ₹15,000–20,000 in electricity bills — easily offsetting its higher purchase price.
        Always check the BEE star label when buying high-consumption appliances.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mistake-card">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="w-5 h-5 text-danger flex-shrink-0" aria-hidden="true"><path d="m21.73 18-8-14a2 2 0 0 0-3.48 0l-8 14A2 2 0 0 0 4 21h16a2 2 0 0 0 1.73-3Z" /><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13" /><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17" /></svg>
    <div>
      <strong>Comparing bills without normalising for days in the billing cycle</strong>
      <p style="margin:0.25rem 0 0;font-size:0.875rem;color:var(--text-muted);">
        Some DISCOM billing cycles are 30 days, others 60 days. Comparing a 60-day bill of 500 units
        to a 30-day bill of 300 units might seem like consumption dropped — but it actually increased
        per day. Always calculate units-per-day (units ÷ days-in-cycle) for apples-to-apples comparisons.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

