  <!-- ─── FAQs ─── -->
  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="kh-faq">
    <details>
      <summary>
        How many units does a 1.5 Ton AC use per month?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A 3-star 1.5 Ton AC (approximately 1,600W) running 8 hours per day uses about 12.8 kWh per day,
        which equals roughly 384 units per month. A 5-star inverter 1.5 Ton AC typically uses 30–40%
        less — around 240–280 units per month under the same conditions. If your AC runs only 6 hours
        per day, divide proportionally: 1,600 × 6 × 30 ÷ 1,000 = 288 units/month.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Is 200 units of electricity per month a lot for a home?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        200 units per month is considered moderate consumption for an Indian home. It's typical for
        a 2 BHK household without AC, or a 1 BHK with light AC usage. In most Indian states, this falls
        within the first two slabs of the tariff structure, so you'll pay a relatively low per-unit rate.
        Above 300–500 units/month (varies by state), you typically enter higher slab rates of ₹7–10/unit.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        How can I reduce my electricity consumption at home?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        The highest-impact changes, in order: (1) Set AC to 24–26°C instead of 18–20°C — each degree
        lower increases consumption by ~6%. (2) Use ceiling fans with AC — allows setting AC 2°C higher
        while maintaining comfort. (3) Switch to 5-star inverter AC when replacing old units.
        (4) Replace old CFL/tube lights with LEDs. (5) Eliminate standby loads with smart switches
        or power strips. (6) Use a solar rooftop system — covered in our Solar & Inverter sizing guide.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        What is the difference between kW and units (kWh) on my bill?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        kW (kilowatt) measures power — how fast electricity is being consumed at any instant, like
        a speedometer reading. kWh (kilowatt-hour) measures energy — the total electricity consumed
        over time, like an odometer. Your electricity bill charges you for kWh (units).
        A 2 kW load running for 3 hours = 6 kWh = 6 units billed. See our detailed
        <a href="/knowledge-hub/load-calculation/kw-vs-kva-vs-kwh-explained" data-astro-prefetch="hover">kW vs kVA vs kWh guide</a> for a full explanation.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        How do I read my electricity meter to track daily usage?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        Your electricity meter (whether analog dial-type or digital) shows a cumulative reading in kWh.
        Read it at the same time each day (e.g., 8:00 PM). Subtract yesterday's reading from today's
        reading to get your daily consumption in units (kWh). Most modern smart meters also display
        instant power draw (in kW) and have a data port that your DISCOM can query remotely. If your
        meter has an LED that blinks, each blink typically represents 1 Wh — 1,000 blinks = 1 unit.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>
        Does a refrigerator really run 24 hours a day?
        <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4.22 6.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L8 8.94l2.72-2.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-3.25 3.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L4.22 7.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" /></svg>
      </summary>
      <div class="faq-body">
        A refrigerator is plugged in 24/7, but its compressor cycles on and off automatically to maintain
        the set temperature. A typical 250L refrigerator has a compressor duty cycle of about 30–50% —
        meaning the compressor runs for roughly 8–12 hours per day and rests for the other 12–16 hours.
        The energy label's "Annual Consumption" figure already accounts for this cycling. Avoid placing
        the fridge near heat sources (oven, direct sunlight) as this increases compressor run-time and
        electricity consumption by 10–20%.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

